==English==
===Etymology===
From a prominent clergyman Bishop Barker in [[Sydney]], [[Australia]] in the 1850s noted for his [[height]].   The expression became obsolete in the 1870s.  (Reference: Bill Wannan, ''Australian Folklore'', Lansdowne Press, 1970, reprint 1979 ISBN 0-7018-1309-1.)
===Noun===
'''[[bishop|Bishop]] [[Barker]]'''
# {{AU}} {{slang}} {{obsolete}} A very tall glass of [[beer]].
#: 1898: ''For a "Bishop Barker" he would compose a quatrain on any subject &ndash; a person preferred &ndash; suggested by the man who tipped him the drink'' &mdash; short story ''Dictionary Ned'' by Price Warung in his collection ''Half-Crown Bob and Tales of the Riverine'', 1898 (quoted by Wannan).
